Why President Bush should not be re-elected
I have never been particularly politically active, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush jeopardizes the safety of the United States and the world while simultaneously undermining American values.
Because of my opposition to him, I was cursed by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 on a campaign promising a foreign policy of "humility."
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote in favor of the Bush doctrine of preventive war—and the invasion of Iraq—and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the polls, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
However, they have also led to the suspension of the critical process so essential to democracy—the comprehensive and honest discussion of the pending problems.
Bush silenced the criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For 18 months following September 11th, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush played Osama bin Laden directly into his hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al-Qaeda maintained their training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not it.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11th, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America occurred all over the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
More people are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans than on September 11th.
Bush often claims that terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day—perhaps twenty times as many.
Just as little was the torture of prisoners in the Abu Ghraib prison the work of a few "rotten apples."
She was part of a system established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld for dealing with prisoners.
The international community condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the September 11 attacks.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign is based on the assumption that people ultimately aren't interested in the truth and almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America when we fall for it.
For example, approximately 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in the September 11 attacks, even though the September 11th Commission—appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican—clearly concluded that no such connection existed.
One would like to scream: "Wake up, America."
"Don't you notice that we're being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from the beginning to the end — if it ever came to an end.
It was a war of choice, not of necessity.
Even more so, America went to war under a pretext: no weapons of mass destruction were found, and the link to Al-Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to free Iraq.
But one cannot impose democracy on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis—and the world—can be glad they are rid of him.
But America had the duty to ensure law and order; instead, we stood idly by as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If it had really been about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would have had to protect not only the ministry of oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods—such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners—that shocked and humiliated the population, thereby inciting bitterness and anger.
The retreats and missteps of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to restore it.
First, the United States tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, the United States installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protégé with a reputation as a "strong man" — a decision anything but democratic.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq remains bleak.
A large part of the western region was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused America incalculable damage, weakened its military strength, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an overwhelming impression of strength.
Not anymore today.
Afghanistan is slipping from control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none of them is as significant as Iraq.
The cost of the war so far amounts to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush taunted John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglements.
But it will not be easy for him either, for America is stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats have urgently warned Bush not to invade Iraq.
He ignored her.
He suppressed the critical process, arguing that any criticism of the commanding officer would endanger the US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment to pause and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection might raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy demeanor qualify him to remain America's top commander?
